Please translate each line literally into English.
1 Imagini, chi bene intender cupe 2 quel ch’i’ or vidi—e ritegna l’image, 3 mentre ch’io dico, come ferma rupe—,
4 quindici stelle che ’n diverse plage 5 lo ciel avvivan di tanto sereno 6 che soperchia de l’aere ogne compage;
7 imagini quel carro a cu’ il seno 8 basta del nostro cielo e notte e giorno, 9 sì ch’al volger del temo non vien meno;
10 imagini la bocca di quel corno 11 che si comincia in punta de lo stelo 12 a cui la prima rota va dintorno,
13 aver fatto di sé due segni in cielo, 14 qual fece la figliuola di Minoi 15 allora che sentì di morte il gelo;
16 e l’un ne l’altro aver li raggi suoi, 17 e amendue girarsi per maniera 18 che l’uno andasse al primo e l’altro al poi;
19 e avrà quasi l’ombra de la vera 20 costellazione e de la doppia danza 21 che circulava il punto dov’ io era:
22 poi ch’è tanto di là da nostra usanza, 23 quanto di là dal mover de la Chiana 24 si move il ciel che tutti li altri avanza.

query.result:
1 Imagine, whoever can well understand deeply 2 what I saw then—and hold the image, 3 while I speak, like a steadfast cliff—,
4 fifteen stars that in different regions 5 enliven the sky with so much serenity 6 that it surpasses every composition of the air;
7 imagine that chariot whose breast 8 suffices for our sky both night and day, 9 so that it does not diminish at the turning of the pole;
10 imagine the mouth of that horn 11 that begins at the tip of the axis 12 around which the first wheel turns,
13 to have made two signs of itself in the sky, 14 like the daughter of Minos did 15 when she felt the frost of death;
16 and the one to have its rays in the other, 17 and both to turn in such a way 18 that one went to the first and the other to the next;
19 and it will have almost the shadow of the true 20 constellation and of the double dance 21 that circled the point where I was:
22 since it is as far beyond our experience 23 as the sky that surpasses all the others 24 moves beyond the movement of the Chiana.

28 The singing and the circling of its measure ended;
29 and those holy lights turned to us,
30 blessing themselves from care to care.

52 That which does not die and that which can die 53 is nothing but the splendor of that idea 54 that our Lord begets, in loving;
55 for that living light which so emanates 56 from its luminous source, which is not separated 57 from it nor from the love that interweaves with them,
58 by its goodness gathers its radiance, 59 as if reflected, into nine subsistences, 60 eternally remaining one.

